Wrangle and Visualize Data

Create a new data set with the species name in replace of 1 and 2 in species column

palmetto_species <- palmetto %>% 
  mutate(species = case_when(
    species == "1" ~ "Serenoa repens",
    species == "2" ~ "Sabal Etonia"
  ))

Use ggpairs to compare data

palmetto_species %>% 
  select(species, height:green_lvs) %>% 
  ggpairs(aes(color = species))

Create a subset with only:

  • species
  • height
  • canopy length
  • canopy width
  • green leaves
palmetto_subset <- palmetto_species %>% 
  select(species, height:green_lvs) %>% 
  drop_na()

Plot 1

ggplot(data = palmetto_subset,
       aes(x = height)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, fill = "darkolivegreen4", color = "darkolivegreen") +
  facet_wrap(~ species) +
  labs(title = "Number of Individuals of Each\nPalmetto Species at Different Heights",
       x = "Height (cm)",
       y = "Number of Individuals") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "aliceblue"))

Figure 1. Number of Individuals of Each Palmetto Species at Different Heights. The population count of Sabal etonia (species 1) and Serenoa repens (species 2) is 6155 and 6112, respectively. Species 1 has a maximum height at 180 cm, and minimum height at 29 cm, and a mean height at 90.090658 cm. Species 2 has a maximum height at 196 cm, and minimum height at 12 cm, and a mean height at 92.189627 cm. For both species 1 and species 2, they have a standard deviation of 24.1681878 and 28.1080658, respectively.

Plot 2

ggplot(data = palmetto_subset,
       aes(x = species, y = green_lvs)) +
  geom_boxplot(color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Number of Green Leaves \nBetween Two Palmetto Species",
       x = "Species",
       y = "Count of Green Leaves") +
  theme_gray() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "aliceblue"))

Figure 2. Number of Green Leaves Between Two Palmetto Species. The number of individuals of Sabal etonia (species 1) and Seriona repens (species 2) is 6155 and 6155, respectively. Species 1 has four outliers and species 2 has 8 outliers. For species 1, the maximum number of leaves an individual has is 12, the minimum number of leaves an individual has is 0, and the median number of leaves for all of the individuals is 4. This first quantile of species 1 is 3 leaves per individual and the third quantile is 5 leaves per individual. For species 2, the maximum number of leaves an individual has is 19, the minimum number of leaves an individual has is 1, and the median number of leaves for all of the individuals is 7. This first quantile of species 2 is 3 leaves per individual and the third quantile is 9 leaves per individual.

Plot 3

ggplot(data = palmetto_subset,
       aes(x = length, y = width)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = green_lvs),
             size = 0.3) +
  facet_wrap(~ species) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "green", high = "yellow") +
  labs(title = "Width of Individual Palmetto Species and\ntheir Green Leave Count Based on Length",
       x = "Length(cm)",
       y = "Width (cm)") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "aliceblue"))

Figure 3. Width of Individual Palmetto Species and their Green Leave Count Based on Length. Width is measured in centimeters and is a function of the length of an individual, also in centimeters. Number of green leaves is also graphed based on both length and width, with 19 being the maximum number of leaves and 0 being the smallest number of leaves on an individual.
